{{Infobox university |name = Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies |native_name = 평양외국어대학 |image_name = |image_size = |image_alt = |caption = |latin_name = |motto = |mottoeng = |established = |closed = |type = [[Public university|Public]] |affiliation = |endowment = |officer_in_charge = |chairman = |chancellor = |president = |vice-president = |superintendent = |provost = |vice_chancellor = |rector = |principal = |dean = |director = |head_label = |head = |faculty = |staff = |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |other = |city = [[Pyongyang]] |state = |province = |country = [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] |coor = |campus = |former_names = |free_label = |free = |sports = |colors = |colours = |nickname = |mascot = |athletics = |affiliations = |website = |logo = |footnotes = }}
{{Infobox Korean name|hangul=평양외국어대학|hanja=平壤外國語大學|rr=Pyeongyang Oegugeo Daehak|mr=Pyŏngyang Oegugŏ Taehak|context=north}}
The '''Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies''' is a 5-year [[university]] in [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]], specializing in [[language education]].
==History==
The university was split off from [[Kim Il-sung University]] in 1964.<ref name="MJ">{{cite news|url=http://www.minjog21.com/news/read.php?idxno=2404|title=과학기술중시정책 영향... 외국어 배우기 열풍, 2개 국어 회화 필수|publisher=Minjog21|last=Yi|first=Jae-seung|date=2007-07-23}}</ref> North Korea's state-run [[Korean Central News Agency]] gives its foundation date as 1949.<ref name="KCNA">{{cite news|url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2009/200911/news24/20091124-12ee.html|title=Pyongyang Univ. of Foreign Studies|work=Korean Central News Agency|date=2009-11-24|accessdate=2010-12-30|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430195205/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2009/200911/news24/20091124-12ee.html|archivedate=2011-04-30|df=}}</ref> It does not have as high a reputation as those of Kim Il-sung University's foreign languages division, which trains members of the political elite; most graduates go on to become working-level diplomats or work in the intelligence service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6231074|title=North Korea's Confusing Brand of English|publisher=National Public Radio|last=Bowers|first=Andy|date=2006-10-10}}</ref>
==Structure== The university has separate colleges for students of [[English language|English]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Japanese language|Japanese]]; the so-called "Ethnic Languages College" offers instruction in a further 18 languages, including [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Arabic]], [[Thai language|Thai]], [[Urdu]], [[Khmer language|Khmer]], and, as of July 2007, [[Polish language|Polish]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=JoongAng Ilbo|date=2007-07-05|accessdate=2007-07-20|title=北평양외대, 폴란드.이태리어科 신설 (Pyongyang Foreign Languages University establishes Polish, Italian courses)|url=http://nk.joins.com/news/view.asp?aid=2950199|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713115404/http://nk.joins.com/news/view.asp?aid=2950199|archivedate=2011-07-13|df=}}</ref>
In total, 22 languages are taught at PUFS:
[[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Khmer language|Khmer]], [[Thai language|Thai]], [[Lao language|Lao]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Hindi]], [[Urdu]], [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minjog21.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=2404 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714100529/http://www.minjog21.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=2404 |archivedate=2011-07-14 |df= }}</ref>
