{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = The 21 Irrefutable Laws of Leadership | image = The 21 Irrefutable Laws of Leadership.jpg | image_size = | alt = Three rectangles on top of each other, the top one black, the middle one red, and the bottom one gold, all with words on them, in gold, white, and black, respectively | caption = First edition cover | author = [[John C. Maxwell]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | release_number = | subject = [[Leadership]] | genre = [[Self-help book]] | set_in = | published = 1998 ([[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]]) | publisher = | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 256 | awards = | isbn = 978-0-785-27431-5 | isbn_note = | oclc = 124074806 | dewey = 658.4/092 | congress = HD57.7.M3937 2007 | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }} '''''The 21 Irrefutable Laws of Leadership: Follow Them and People Will Follow You''''' is a 1998 book written by [[John C. Maxwell]] and published by [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]].{{sfn|Maxwell|1998}} It is one of several [[List of books by John C. Maxwell|books by Maxwell]] on the subject of [[leadership]].<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|title=Shopping Center Trade Show Returns with Renewed Enthusiasm|author=Velotta, Richard N.|date=May 15, 2015|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/retail/shopping-center-trade-show-returns-renewed-enthusiasm|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> It is the book for which he is best-known.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|title=John Maxwell Unveils 'Five Levels of Leadership'|author=Martin, Mark|date=January 9, 2012|url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/finance/2012/January/John-Maxwell-Unveils-Five-Levels-of-Leadership/|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> The book was listed on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] in April 1999<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The New York Times Book Review]]|title=The New York Times Business Best Sellers|date=April 11, 1999|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/11/business/the-new-york-times-business-best-sellers.html|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> after marketing company [[ResultSource]] manipulated the list by making it look like copies of ''The 21 Irrefutable Laws of Leadership'' had been purchased by thousands of individuals when, in actuality, ResultSource had simply made a bulk order of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Christianity Today]]|title=Is Buying Your Way Onto the Bestseller List Wrong?|author=Walker, Ken|date=January 20, 2015|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2015/januaryfebruary/buying-bestsellers-resultsource.html|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> The book had sold more than one million copies by 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana]]|title=Reader Reminds John C. Maxwell Ranks as Leader for Speaking|date=March 12, 2015|author=Potempa, Phil|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/offbeat-with-phil-potempa-reader-reminds-john-c-maxwell-ranks/article_a7e2e5c4-a2ef-5561-bcf3-cb583731ddad.html|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Christian businessperson John Faulkner was inspired to found Christian business magazine ''TwoTen'' when he read ''The 21 Irrefutable Laws of Leadership''.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|title='TwoTen' Magazine Looks to Promote Christian Principles in the Workplace|author=Whitman, Sarah|date=September 1, 2012|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/humaninterest/twoten-magazine-looks-to-promote-christian-principles-in-the-workplace/1249047|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Professional basketball player [[Harrison Barnes]] read and spoke positively of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Adweek]]|title=NBA Star Creates Buzz With His Popular Twitter Scavenger Hunts: Golden State's Social Media-Savvy Harrison Barnes|author=Bazilian, Emma|date=January 30, 2014|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/nba-star-creates-buzz-his-popular-twitter-scavenger-hunts-155193|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Annie Grevers of ''[[Swimming World Magazine]]'' wrote of Maxwell's book, "it's cheesy, but ... it did me some good".<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|author=Grevers, Annie|title=6 Types of Team Captain No One Wants|date=August 24, 2015|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/6-types-of-team-captain-no-one-wants/|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> Columnist [[Michael Hiltzik]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' criticized Maxwell for including in the book "the insidious subtext ... that externalities have nothing to do with your failure", an assertion that Hiltzik argues research studies have demonstrated to be false.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=[[Michael Hiltzik|Hiltzik, Michael]]|title=More on What Makes the 1% So Darned Wonderful, by Yet Another Courtier|date=October 7, 2014|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-what-makes-the-20141007-column.html|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>
